ostinho.","Portuguese and Galician: patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Lopo</i> (from Latin <i>lupus</i> ‘wolf’).","Spanish: variant or altered form of <b>López</b> (see   Lopez  )."]},{"name":"Lope","meanings":["Spanish: from the old personal name <i>Lope</i>, from Latin <i>lupus</i> ‘wolf’."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Haro","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jesus, Juan, Luis, Salvador, Manuel, Carlos, Jorge, Miguel, Alberto, Francisco, Jaime.","Spanish: habitational name from a place in the province of La Rioja, so called from a North Castilian form of Spanish <i>faro</i> ‘beacon’. Compare   De Haro  .","In some cases possibly also French: metonymic occupational name for a peddler, from an Old French cry used to hail someone or to attract attention."],"variants":[{"name":"De Haro","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Rafael, Arturo, Jaime, Jesus, Ubaldo, Alfredo, Enrique, Felipe, Francisco, Gustavo, Juan.","Spanish: habitational name, formed with the preposition <i>de</i> ‘from’, for someone from a place called Haro (see   Haro  )."]},{"name":"Haros","meanings":["Hispanic (mainly Mexico): probably the plural form of Spanish   Haro  .","Greek: varian